{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958061901/0367.xml":{"full_text":"J^WASHINGTON\nMARCH OF EVENTS\nCofta Consumption in U. Java Gulping AetuoMy Rose\nNot Affected by Recession I During Depression of *3os\nBy HENRY CATHCART\nCentral Press Washington Writer\nWASHINGTON\u2014 The coffee market, vitally important to South\nAmerica, is not one of those directly troubled by United\nStates policies, either foreign or domestic. The Pan-American Coffee\nbureau in Washington has come up with an unusual economic in\ndicator to show that the present U. S. recession hasn\u2019t sunk to the\ndepression level yet.\nThe bureau reports that there is no evidence\nyet that coffee sales in the United States have\nbeen seriously affected by the recession, although\nprices have been steadily dropping for months\nas a result of heavy supplies.\nIn contrast to present sales, the bureau notes,\nduring the depression of the 1930 s coffee prices\nalso dropped to very low levels but consumption\nactually increased at that time.\nThe analysis seems to indicate that people\ndrink more coffee when they have financial wor\nries in \u201cbad times\u201d than they do in periods of\nprosperity.\n\nMILITARY OVERHAUL\u2014 Look for the fight\nWashington\non reorganization of the Pentagon to. be one of the last items of\nbusiness of an unusually long off-year election session of Congress.\nThe House armed services committee is not expected to complete\nIts version of a defense reorganization bill until at least June 1.\nEven after House action is completed, the President\u2019s Pentagon\nplan faces a formidable hurdle in the Senate, since Armed Services\nChairman Richard B. Russell (D), Georgia, has expressed senti\nments similar to those of his fellow Georgian, Rep. Carl Vinson.\nVinson, the House armed services chairman, is the leader of the\nadministration\u2019s critics on the military reshuffle issue. All in all,\nit will be late July or early August before any compromise is likely\nto clear Congress and go to the President.\nCongressmen usually like to end election-year sessions by mid-\nJuly so they will have, plenty of time to convince voters they de\n\u2022erve to keep their $25,000-a-year jobs.\nHowever, that isn\u2019t likely this year. August 15 is a more frequent\nguess for adjournment, partly because of the controversy over the\nmilitary reorganization plan.\n\nECONOMY REPORT\u2014 Commerce Secretary Sinclair Weeks ana\nother administration officials (who have insisted that the recession\nIsn\u2019t as bad as the Democrats have painted it) point to a number\nOf encouraging signs on the economic front.\nThey cite these facts:\nSteel production is climbing. Auto dealers report they sold\n708,500 used cars in April, only 9.8 per cent below the volume for\nApril, 1957, and they say that this foreshadows an\nUpturn in new car sales. Cloth Sales,\nAlso, textile industry sources report that the\nslump in cloth sales and prices has been halted. A\nleading farm equipment firm said its sales for the Have Halted\n\u2022ix months ended April 30 were five per cent above\nthe figure for the first half of the previous fiscal year.\nThe nation\u2019s biggest mail order house called its April sales \u201cde\ncidedly encouraging.\u201d Sears, Roebuck Chairman Theodore V.\nHouser, in making the report, predicted a general upswing for the\nentire economy by September or October.\nHeaHh^'S^^\nuto\nPlastic surgery for such simple I\ndefects as flyaway ears and a\ntoo-large nose have become as\ncommonplace as having child-\nren\u2019s teeth straightened. There\nis no longer any excuse for a\nperson to go through life with\na nose or a pair of ears that\ncause him to be unhappy. The\noperation is often very simple 1\nand the cost in money is nothing\ncompared with the improvement\nin personality and happiness that 1\nit can bring. 1\nMany more complicated plastic\nsurgery operations are being\nperformed, and will be, before\nTHINKING\n